When your website needs to interact with a database you use &lt;strong&gt;SQL&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;Structured Query Language&lt;/strong&gt; to talk to the database.<br />
<br />
In this case it looks like you have a web application probably written in PHP on your website that is trying to use a SQL query to select some information, but there is a syntax error in that question.<br />
<br />
MySQL is trying to tell you that the improper syntax happened on &lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;line 1&lt;/span&gt; where it looks like &lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;SQL=SELECT css FROM jos_formmaker_themes WHERE id=&lt;/span&gt;<br />
<br />
You usually would need to modify the SQL code to use the proper syntax, but unfortunately you wouldn't know what the proper syntax is unless you saw the entire query or compared it to the database.<br />
<br />
For instance if that line simply ended with &lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;WHERE id=&lt;/span&gt; then it would be an incomplete &lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;WHERE&lt;/span&gt; clause, as it would need to be passed an &lt;span style=&quot;color: red;&quot;&gt;id&lt;/span&gt; number. So possibly your website form isn't correctly passing that value to your script and that's why it's failing.<br />
<br />
- Jacob</div>
